<br>
I don't see how someone's post count can add to one's credibility regarding a game.<br>
<br>
If I want to know how &quot;credible&quot; a person is as a gamer, I play the damn game with them.  That's how you know how they play and if they play clean or not.  <br>
<br>
I have interacted with people on the msg boards for a long while, but not once have I backed up an acquaintance whose reputation in-game was attacked.  I've never played with them, thus I have no opinion of what sort of player they are.  They could be the biggest sweethearts on the message board and the biggest morons in a dungeon- I'll never know.  Thus, I keep my trap shut.<br>
<br>
For me, interacting through the game and communicating through a forum are two completely separate things.  To say one's post count determines one's credibility is base, judgemental and incredibly superficial.  <br>
<br>
I may have 100+ posts to my name here on EMarr, but what does that say about me?  It says I have friends on this board I love to interact with, I have enemies here I love to piss off, I'm bored and I'm not playing EQ.  I don't see how any of those affect my credibility.  So if, let's say, Ghalewind came in and posted some bullshit and we see he has 100+ posts.  Does that make him suddenly credible?  How about Mistywolf?<br>
<br>
I fail to see how there is any connection between credibility and message board posts.  If you want real credibility, go out and group with the people.  It doesn't matter if you've interacted with them over and over again on a message board, you still don't know how they play the game, thus you are lacking sufficient information you need to make a formulated opinion.  Post counts mean shit.  I know plenty of hard-core, honest to God, fine players who rarely frequent this board.  Let me repeat myself.  Post counts mean shit.  Want a /real/ opinion?  Do the work and go play with the people on EQ.  <br>
<br>
People like you, Ogma, are dangerous.  You seem to think there is a way to formulate a valid opinion about a person's persona just through a stale number.  People used to think a person's religious affiliation could be measured by the number of moles on their body, and if they found one they didn't like, they hanged the wench.  Faith used to be able to be measured by sinking an accused woman of witchcraft in water.  If she drowned, she was indeed faithful, yet if she floated and survived, she lacked it and was indeed a soldier of Satan.  It's all the same to me.  It's all generalizations and assumptions.  But, it's those very generalizations and assumptions that are dangerous.  Why?  Because they are lacking in wisdom and common sense.  An ounce of common sense can do wonders, but I don't think you can understand that.<br>
<br>
I suggest you cease to reply, because you've already branded and labeled yourself a useless, superficial, and arrogant individual who has nothing useful nor positive to add to intelligent conversations.  Your rhetoric is ghey.  Your points are dull and lacking in merit.  You are, overall, blasé.  Your arguments cannot stand on their own, thus you change your arguments whenever it so suits you.<br>
<br>
Only the pompous, immature and ignorant believe the masses can be categorized simply to their liking.  Take that any way you wish to, but I'd prefer if you took it the worst way because that'll be closer to how it was originally intended to come across.<br>
