</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/bemarr.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=gieve>Gieve</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 53<br> <font color=#E9D756>(10/5/01 1:30:54 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Finally</span><hr size=1> I feel compelled to add my useless 2 cents into this argument.<br>
<br>
I think Ogma is being seriously misunderstood.  If you go back and reread his posts before he got into the pissing contest with Trech, I think his actual point has been overlooked.<br>
<br>
It seems to me that what he is trying to say is this:<br>
<br>
There are many different ways to form an opinion of someone from EQ.  You can play with them in game.  You can have discussions with them here or on some other message board.  You can talk to others you trust and get thier experiences with the person.  Or you can read the things they have to say on this board.  Or any of a dozen other ways I am sure.<br>
<br>
If someone posts here, and that post basically asks you to change your opinion about someone or something else, you have to decide for yourself what to think about it.  If you do not know the poster, and no one you know or trust backs him up, all you have to go on at that point is thier other posts here.  Do they tell you anything about the poster, good or bad?  If there are no other posts to help you here, you have nothing to go on.  Therefore you should take everything said with a grain of salt until you can get it verified (if you even care enough to do so).<br>
<br>
This leaves us at the original point:<br>
<br>
The posts (or lack thereof) can HELP you determine your opinion (or lack thereof) on the matter.  But number of posts is by no means a fair way to judge someone.  If they have posted a lot previously, you probably have formed an opinion of that person's moral character.  Maybe.  That is up to you.  If they have not, and you have no other information upon which to act, maybe you should consider not judging anyone involved just yet.<br>
<br>
